.org/city/charlotte/CityCouncil/MeettheCouncil/Pages/Ed-Driggs.aspx  | accessdate = 24 December 2014}}</ref>\n| unit_pref               = US\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>{{cite web | title = Quality of Life Explorer  (acres) | publisher = City of Charlotte, Mecklenburg County, and UNCC | url = http://mcmap.org/qol/?m=m1&n=355,253,189,187,188,169,257,75,255,356  | accessdate = 3 May 2015}}</ref>\n| area_urban_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_rural_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_metro_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_magnitude          = <!-- use only to set a special wikilink -->\n| area_note               = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_blank1_title       = \n| area_blank2_title       = \n<!-- square miles -->\n| area_total_sq_mi        =  \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n| area_urban_sq_mi        = \n| area_rural_sq_mi        = \n| area_metro_sq_mi        = \n| area_blank1_sq_mi       = \n| area_blank2_sq_mi       = \n<!-- acres -->\n| area_total_acre         = 5114\n| area_land_acre          = \n| area_water_acre         = \n| area_urban_acre         = \n| area_rural_acre         = \n| area_metro_acre         = \n| area_blank1_acre        = \n| area_blank2_acre        = \n| length_mi               = \n| width_mi                = \n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_ft            = \n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=Demographics>{{cite web | title = Quality of Life Explorer (population) | publisher = City of Charlotte, Mecklenburg County, and UNCC | url = http://mcmap.org/qol/?m=m47&n=355,253,189,187,188,169,257,75,255,356  | accessdate = 7 May 2016}}</ref>\n| population_total        = 70,582\n| population_as_of        = 2016\n| population_density_sq_mi= auto\n| population_demonym      =  \n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]]\n| utc_offset1             = -5\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = -4\n| postal_code_type        = Zip Code\n| postal_code             = 28277 \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = 704, 980\n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = [http://maps.co.mecklenburg.nc.us/qoldashboard/index.html Quality of Life Dashboard]\n}}\n'''Ballantyne''' is a  [[neighborhood]] in the city of [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], occupying a {{convert|2000|acre|km2|sing=on}} area of land adjacent to the [[South Carolina]] border. The neighborhood is home to [[St. Matthew Catholic Church (Charlotte, North Carolina)|St. Matthew Catholic Church]], the largest Catholic congregation in the United States.\n\nIn June 2013, [[Wingate University]] announced that it was moving its [[Matthews, NC|Matthews]] campus to Ballantyne.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/blog/real_estate/2013/06/wingate-university-to-open-ballantyne.html Wingate University to open Ballantyne campus in August]</ref>\n\n==History==\nBallantyne was originally a large hunting tract owned by the Harris family, descendants of former [[Governor of North Carolina|North Carolina governor]] [[Cameron A. Morrison]].<ref name=Markovitch>{{cite web |url=https://www.ourstate.com/being-ballantyne-in-the-always-new-charlotte/ |title=Being Ballantyne in the Always New Charlotte |work=[[Our State]] |author=Markovitch, Jeremy |date=March 2, 2016 |accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> In 1992, Johnny Harris and his brother-in-law, Smoky Bissell, started Ballantyne Corporate Park, which has become one of the most successful master-planned communities in the United States. Harris had the 2,000 acres rezoned, the largest in Mecklenburg county history. Another developer, Crescent Resources, had already purchased the 610 acres that would later become the Ballantyne Country Club and the accompanying residential development.<ref name=Newsome>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlottemagazine.com/Charlotte-Magazine/December-2012/Theres-Something-About-Ballantyne/ |title=There's Something About Ballantyne |work=Charlotte Magazine |author=Newsome, Melba |date=November 19, 2012 |accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> In October 1995, Bissell bought out his brothers-in-law\u2019s shares for $20 million and established Ballantyne, named after his great aunt. Bissell also developed and designed the Ballantyne Hotel, which opened in September 2001.\n\nAt the intersection of Johnston Road and Ballantyne Commons stand four 30-foot monuments representing transportation, technology, finance, and the human spirit of Charlotte. The art installation was commissioned by [[Yugoslavia]]n artist Boris Tomic, who spent three years crafting them at a brick factory in [[Salisbury, North Carolina|Salisbury]].<ref name=Newsome />\n\n==Ballantyne Corporate Park==\nBallantyne Corporate Park is a {{convert|535|acre|ha}} acre business park. With over {{convert|4000000|sqft|m2}} of [[Class A office space]], the business park includes the headquarters of [[Babcock & Wilcox]], [[Curtiss-Wright]], [[Lending tree|Tree.com Inc]], [[Lance Inc.|Snyder's-Lance Inc]], [[Premier, Inc.|Premier Inc]], Extended Stay America, Inc, [[SPX Corporation|SPX]], and ESPN regional television.<ref>[http://www.go-ballantyne.com/Information/CorporateParkDirectory.aspx Ballantyne Corporate Park Directory]</ref> Brighthouse Financial, TIAA, and Wells Fargo also have a major corporate presence in Ballantyne.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/print-edition/2013/04/19/bissells-ballantyne-bet-pays-off.html?page=all Bissell's Ballantyne bet pays off]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Ballantyne Corporate Park was recognized as International Office Park of the Year by the Building Owners and Managers Association International (BOMA).\n\nIn 2017, H.C. \"Smoky\" Bissell, who developed Ballantyne Corporate Park, sold the development for $1.2 billion to Northwood Investors, becoming the largest transaction in Charlotte real estate history.<ref name=Portillo>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/business/biz-columns-blogs/development/article137179453.html |title=Behind the scenes on Ballantyne\u2019s $1.2 billion sale: \u2018A deal that wanted to be made\u2019|work=Charlotte Observer |author=Portillo, Eli |date=March 8, 2018 |accessdate=March 8, 2010}}</ref> In an effort to transform Ballantyne from a corporate park into a walk-able, dense community, Northwood announced plans to construct a 25 acre mixed-use development on the current site of The Golf Club at Ballantyne. Phase I of the development includes 1,200 multifamily units, 300,000 square feet of retail, an amphitheater, multiple parks, and a greenway. Phase II includes an additional 1,000 multifamily units, 300 townhomes, and 400,000 square feet of additional office space.<ref>http://reimagined.projectballantyne.com/phasing/</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|2000= 9466\n|2010= 20936\n|estyear=2015\n|estimate= 23495\n|footnote= <ref name=Demographics/>\n}}\nAs of 2011, Ballantyne had a population of 20,936. The racial makeup of the neighborhood was 69.2% [[White American]], 11.3% [[Asian American]], 10.3% [[Black (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[African American]], and 2.5% of [[Race (United States Census)|some other race]]. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino American]] of any race were 6.7% of the population. The median household income for the area was $96,435.<ref>{{cite web | title = Quality of Life Explorer | publisher = City of Charlotte, Mecklenburg County, and UNCC | url = http://mcmap.org/qol/  | accessdate = 3 May 2015}}</ref> \n\n==Controversies==\n\nOn April 14, 2012, residents met to discuss an idea of breaking away from the city of Charlotte to form their own city.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/04/11/3171583/a-divorce-for-charlotte-and-ballantyne.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-04-14 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120722075558/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/04/11/3171583/a-divorce-for-charlotte-and-ballantyne.html |archive-date=2012-07-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the history of North Carolina, this has never been done before. If it is done, the residents will name the new city Providence. However, there is currently{{when|date=February 2015}} a North Carolina community that already carries this name and has its own zip code.<ref>https://www.zipdatamaps.com/27315</ref>\n\n==Printed media==\n*''Ballantyne'' magazine\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Charlotte/Ballantyne|Ballantyne}}\n*''[http://www.ballantynemagazine.com/ Ballantyne]'' magazine\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Ballantyne, Charlotte\n|North = Whiteoak, Charlotte\n|Northeast = Piper Glenn, Charlotte\n|East = Provincetowne, Charlotte\n|Southeast = [[Marvin, North Carolina]]\n|South = \n|Southwest = [[Indian Land, South Carolina]]\n|West = Unincorporated Mecklenburg County\n|Northwest = Johnston Road/McAlpine, Charlotte<br>Highway 51-Park Road\n}}\n{{Charlotte, North Carolina}}\n\n{{coord|35.054659|-80.850238|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ballantyne (Neighborhood)}}\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Charlotte, North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "ScottSki22", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversies", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ballantyne_(Charlotte_neighborhood)"}
{"title_page": "Karl Yoneda", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name=Karl Yoneda\n|image=KarlYoneda.jpg\n|caption=At Manzanar internment camp, 1942 <br>(Photo: [[Dorothea Lange]])\n|birth_name=Goso Yoneda\n|birth_date=July 15, 1906\n|birth_place=[[Glendale, California]]\n|death_date={{Death year and age|1999|1906}}\n|known_for=[[International Longshore and Warehouse Union]]<br />[[Communist Party USA|Communist Party]] organizer\n}}\n\n'''Karl Gozo Yoneda''' ({{lang-ja|\u7c73\u7530\u525b\u4e09}}, 1906&ndash;1999) was a [[Japanese American]] activist, [[labor union|union]] organizer, World War II veteran and author. He played a substantial role in the founding of the [[International Longshore and Warehouse Union]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Glendale, California]] in 1906 to [[Japanese people|Japanese]] immigrants, Hideo and Kazu.  In 1913, Yoneda's father, now diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]], took the family to [[Japan]] to live in their native village just outside [[Hiroshima]]. His father died two years later, leaving his mother to raise him and his two sisters.<ref name=\"plaza\">{{cite book | last = Estrada | first = William David | year = 2008 | title = The Los Angeles Plaza: Sacred and Contested Space | url = https://archive.org/details/losangelesplazas0000estr | url-access = registration | location = Austin, Texas | publisher = University of Texas Press | pages = [https://archive.org/details/losangelesplazas0000estr/page/162 162\u2013167]}}</ref>\n\nAfter World War I, Yoneda went to high school in Hiroshima.  When he was 15, he organized a strike among the delivery boys of the powerful ''Chugoku Shimbun'' newspaper. The company had increased the delivery routes without increasing pay.\n\nSuch experiences led Yoneda to progressive ideas. He began reading the works of anarchists and socialists such as [[Karl Marx]], [[Engels]], [[Kropotkin]], [[Bakunin]], and the blind anarchist poet [[Vasili Eroshenko]], whom he hitch-hiked to meet in Beijing when he was 16 years old. He stayed with Eroshenko two months and went back to Japan. There, he participated in workers strikes and began publishing a journal for poor farmers, ''Tsuchi''. For that, he was beaten and thrown into jail.<ref name=\"longshoreman\">{{cite web | last = Price | first = Tom | title = Karl Yoneda, working class hero | url = http://recollectionbooks.com/bleed/Encyclopedia/EroshenkoVasily/people_0599.htm | accessdate = 2014-07-11 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130503180535/http://recollectionbooks.com/bleed/Encyclopedia/EroshenkoVasily/people_0599.htm | archivedate = 2013-05-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Activist life in the U.S.==\n\nIn 1926, Yoneda returned to the U.S. rather than be drafted into the imperial army. On entering the U.S., though he was an American citizen carrying his birth certificate, he was detained at the Immigration Detention House on Angel Island in San Francisco Bay for two months.\n\nHe changed his name to Karl to honor Karl Marx and worked as a dish washer and window washer in Los Angeles for $5 a day. He became involved with the Communist Party and the Los Angeles Japanese Workers Association.  About that period, he wrote:\n\n<blockquote>\nI was a young dreamer back then, you know, the utopian type. The Plaza was my very first experience with mass demonstrations. It was easy to go over there because you felt like you were with your own kind of people&mdash;no dressed-up people there, nobody was wearing neckties.<ref name=\"plaza\" />\n</blockquote>\n\nWhen Japan invaded China in 1929, he returned to Japan to protest against the invasion. Marching with the most militant groups, he narrowly escaped being arrested and returned to the U.S.\n\nAt a march in Los Angeles in 1931, the police \"Red Squad\" severely beat him and threw him in a jail cell. The chief called [[Elaine Black Yoneda]], whom the police called the \"Red Angel\" for her work in helping strikers, rushed over, bailed him out, and took him to a hospital, saving his life.<ref name=\"Found\">{{cite web|last=Price|first=Tom|title=Karl Yoneda|url=http://beta.shapingsf-wiki.org/index.php?title=Karl_Yoneda|work=Found SF|accessdate=2013-05-12|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130705020531/http://beta.shapingsf-wiki.org/index.php?title=Karl_Yoneda|archive-date=2013-07-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> The couple soon fell in love. They could not get married, however, because of California's [[Anti-miscegenation laws]]. They borrowed money for a ticket to Seattle, where they were married in 1935.<ref name=\"black\">{{cite book | last = Rainieri | first = Vivian McGuckin | year = 1991 | title = The Red Angel: The Life and Times of Elaine Black Yoneda | location = New York | publisher = International Publishers}}</ref>\n\nThey participated in the largest demonstrations in the city's history. In 1933, after he spoke out against the tactics of the Red Squad before the L.A. City Council, the squad caught him in an elevator and gave him the worst beating of his life. During his three-month recovery, Elaine went to San Francisco to work for the International Labor Defense group. He was offered the job of editing the Japanese Communist publication ''Rodo Shimbun'' and moved to San Francisco to take it.\n\nIn May, 1934, they helped organize and participate in a [[1934 West Coast waterfront strike|longshoremen's strike]] in San Francisco. The bosses and police, determined to stop the strike, opened fire on the strikers, killing two and wounding several others. In 1938, Karl went to Washington State to help organize Alaska cannery workers.<ref name=\"cannery\">{{cite web | last = Pinckney | first = Shelley| title = Communism In Washington State: History and Memory - Chapter 6: Race and Civil Rights: the 30s and 40s | url = http://depts.washington.edu/labhist/cpproject/pinckney.shtml |year=2002 | accessdate = 2014-07-11}}</ref>\n\n==World War II and after==\n\nIn 1942, Karl, Elaine, and son Tom [[Japanese American internment|were unjustly incarcerated]] at [[Manzanar]]. Karl registered for the draft and joined the army in November. He served in the [[Military Intelligence Service (United States)|United States Military Intelligence Service]] as a Japanese language specialist in China, Burma and India.<ref name = \"FindingAid\">{{cite web | title = Finding Aid for the Karl G. Yoneda Papers, 1928-1989 | url = http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf0c6002wh | publisher = UCLA, Special Collections, Young (Charles E.) Research Library | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> He served valiantly and was decorated several times.\n\nAfter the war, Elaine and Karl continued to work throughout their lives for the unions and anti-war efforts. His mother had survived the atom bomb. In 1960, they visited her on the occasion of attending a peace conference in Tokyo.\n\nAfter he retired in 1972, he continued to organize and work for human rights. He lectured, wrote articles and an autobiography,<ref name=\"ganbatte\">{{cite book | last = Yoneda | first = Karl | year = 1983 | title = Ganbatte: Sixty-Year Struggle of a Kibei Worker | url = https://archive.org/details/ganbattesixtyyea00yone | url-access = registration | location = Los Angeles | publisher = UCLA Asian American Studies Center}}.</ref> and kept his membership in the Communist Party. His wife died in 1988, and he died in 1999.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Japanese resistance to the Empire of Japan (1937\u20131945)]] \n* [[Koji Ariyoshi]]\n* [[Elaine Black Yoneda]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lib.washington.edu/specialcoll/findaids/docs/papersrecords/YonedaKarlG1273.xml Karl G. Yoneda papers]. 1868-1969. .03 cubic foot. At the [http://www.lib.washington.edu/specialcoll/laws Labor Archives of Washington , University of Washington Libraries Special Collections].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yoneda, Karl}}\n[[Category:American military personnel of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American civil rights activists]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American internees]]\n[[Category:American journalists of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:People from Glendale, California]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Communist Party USA]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from California]]\n[[Category:International Longshore and Warehouse Union people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name=Karl Yoneda\n|image=KarlYoneda.jpg\n|caption=At Manzanar internment camp, 1942 <br>(Photo: [[Dorothea Lange]])\n|birth_name=Goso Yoneda\n|birth_date=1906\n|birth_place=[[Glendale, California]]\n|death_date={{Death year and age|1999|1906}}\n|known_for=[[International Longshore and Warehouse Union]]<br />[[Communist Party USA|Communist Party]] organizer\n}}\n\n'''Karl Gozo Yoneda''' ({{lang-ja|\u7c73\u7530\u525b\u4e09}}, 1906&ndash;1999) was a [[Japanese American]] activist, [[labor union|union]] organizer, World War II veteran and author. He played a substantial role in the founding of the [[International Longshore and Warehouse Union]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Glendale, California]] in 1906 to [[Japanese people|Japanese]] immigrants, Hideo and Kazu.  In 1913, Yoneda's father, now diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]], took the family to [[Japan]] to live in their native village just outside [[Hiroshima]]. His father died two years later, leaving his mother to raise him and his two sisters.<ref name=\"plaza\">{{cite book | last = Estrada | first = William David | year = 2008 | title = The Los Angeles Plaza: Sacred and Contested Space | url = https://archive.org/details/losangelesplazas0000estr | url-access = registration | location = Austin, Texas | publisher = University of Texas Press | pages = [https://archive.org/details/losangelesplazas0000estr/page/162 162\u2013167]}}</ref>\n\nAfter World War I, Yoneda went to high school in Hiroshima.  When he was 15, he organized a strike among the delivery boys of the powerful ''Chugoku Shimbun'' newspaper. The company had increased the delivery routes without increasing pay.\n\nSuch experiences led Yoneda to progressive ideas. He began reading the works of anarchists and socialists such as [[Karl Marx]], [[Engels]], [[Kropotkin]], [[Bakunin]], and the blind anarchist poet [[Vasili Eroshenko]], whom he hitch-hiked to meet in Beijing when he was 16 years old. He stayed with Eroshenko two months and went back to Japan. There, he participated in workers strikes and began publishing a journal for poor farmers, ''Tsuchi''. For that, he was beaten and thrown into jail.<ref name=\"longshoreman\">{{cite web | last = Price | first = Tom | title = Karl Yoneda, working class hero | url = http://recollectionbooks.com/bleed/Encyclopedia/EroshenkoVasily/people_0599.htm | accessdate = 2014-07-11 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130503180535/http://recollectionbooks.com/bleed/Encyclopedia/EroshenkoVasily/people_0599.htm | archivedate = 2013-05-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Activist life in the U.S.==\n\nIn 1926, Yoneda returned to the U.S. rather than be drafted into the imperial army. On entering the U.S., though he was an American citizen carrying his birth certificate, he was detained at the Immigration Detention House on Angel Island in San Francisco Bay for two months.\n\nHe changed his name to Karl to honor Karl Marx and worked as a dish washer and window washer in Los Angeles for $5 a day. He became involved with the Communist Party and the Los Angeles Japanese Workers Association.  About that period, he wrote:\n\n<blockquote>\nI was a young dreamer back then, you know, the utopian type. The Plaza was my very first experience with mass demonstrations. It was easy to go over there because you felt like you were with your own kind of people&mdash;no dressed-up people there, nobody was wearing neckties.<ref name=\"plaza\" />\n</blockquote>\n\nWhen Japan invaded China in 1929, he returned to Japan to protest against the invasion. Marching with the most militant groups, he narrowly escaped being arrested and returned to the U.S.\n\nAt a march in Los Angeles in 1931, the police \"Red Squad\" severely beat him and threw him in a jail cell. The chief called [[Elaine Black Yoneda]], whom the police called the \"Red Angel\" for her work in helping strikers, rushed over, bailed him out, and took him to a hospital, saving his life.<ref name=\"Found\">{{cite web|last=Price|first=Tom|title=Karl Yoneda|url=http://beta.shapingsf-wiki.org/index.php?title=Karl_Yoneda|work=Found SF|accessdate=2013-05-12|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130705020531/http://beta.shapingsf-wiki.org/index.php?title=Karl_Yoneda|archive-date=2013-07-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> The couple soon fell in love. They could not get married, however, because of California's [[Anti-miscegenation laws]]. They borrowed money for a ticket to Seattle, where they were married in 1935.<ref name=\"black\">{{cite book | last = Rainieri | first = Vivian McGuckin | year = 1991 | title = The Red Angel: The Life and Times of Elaine Black Yoneda | location = New York | publisher = International Publishers}}</ref>\n\nThey participated in the largest demonstrations in the city's history. In 1933, after he spoke out against the tactics of the Red Squad before the L.A. City Council, the squad caught him in an elevator and gave him the worst beating of his life. During his three-month recovery, Elaine went to San Francisco to work for the International Labor Defense group. He was offered the job of editing the Japanese Communist publication ''Rodo Shimbun'' and moved to San Francisco to take it.\n\nIn May, 1934, they helped organize and participate in a [[1934 West Coast waterfront strike|longshoremen's strike]] in San Francisco. The bosses and police, determined to stop the strike, opened fire on the strikers, killing two and wounding several others. In 1938, Karl went to Washington State to help organize Alaska cannery workers.<ref name=\"cannery\">{{cite web | last = Pinckney | first = Shelley| title = Communism In Washington State: History and Memory - Chapter 6: Race and Civil Rights: the 30s and 40s | url = http://depts.washington.edu/labhist/cpproject/pinckney.shtml |year=2002 | accessdate = 2014-07-11}}</ref>\n\n==World War II and after==\n\nIn 1942, Karl, Elaine, and son Tom [[Japanese American internment|were unjustly incarcerated]] at [[Manzanar]]. Karl registered for the draft and joined the army in November. He served in the [[Military Intelligence Service (United States)|United States Military Intelligence Service]] as a Japanese language specialist in China, Burma and India.<ref name = \"FindingAid\">{{cite web | title = Finding Aid for the Karl G. Yoneda Papers, 1928-1989 | url = http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf0c6002wh | publisher = UCLA, Special Collections, Young (Charles E.) Research Library | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> He served valiantly and was decorated several times.\n\nAfter the war, Elaine and Karl continued to work throughout their lives for the unions and anti-war efforts. His mother had survived the atom bomb. In 1960, they visited her on the occasion of attending a peace conference in Tokyo.\n\nAfter he retired in 1972, he continued to organize and work for human rights. He lectured, wrote articles and an autobiography,<ref name=\"ganbatte\">{{cite book | last = Yoneda | first = Karl | year = 1983 | title = Ganbatte: Sixty-Year Struggle of a Kibei Worker | url = https://archive.org/details/ganbattesixtyyea00yone | url-access = registration | location = Los Angeles | publisher = UCLA Asian American Studies Center}}.</ref> and kept his membership in the Communist Party. His wife died in 1988, and he died in 1999.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Japanese resistance to the Empire of Japan (1937\u20131945)]] \n* [[Koji Ariyoshi]]\n* [[Elaine Black Yoneda]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lib.washington.edu/specialcoll/findaids/docs/papersrecords/YonedaKarlG1273.xml Karl G. Yoneda papers]. 1868-1969. .03 cubic foot. At the [http://www.lib.washington.edu/specialcoll/laws Labor Archives of Washington , University of Washington Libraries Special Collections].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yoneda, Karl}}\n[[Category:American military personnel of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American civil rights activists]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American internees]]\n[[Category:American journalists of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:People from Glendale, California]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Communist Party USA]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from California]]\n[[Category:International Longshore and Warehouse Union people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n", "name_user": "E chaikin", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Yoneda"}
{"title_page": "\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Sanctuary", "text_new": "{{Infobox church\n| denomination = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| name = \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Sanctuary\n| other name =  Holy Linden Basilica\n| image = File:\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 Pielgrzymkowy 072.jpg\n| imagesize = 240\n| imagealt = \n| caption = The basilica in 2012\n| pushpin map = \n| pushpin label position = \n| pushpin map alt = \n| relief = \n| pushpin mapsize = \n| map caption = \n| coordinates =\n| country = [[Poland]]\n| osgridref = <!-- {{gbmappingsmall| TEXT}} -->\n| osgraw = <!--  TEXT -->\n| location = [[\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka]], [[Warmia]]\n| previous denomination = \n| churchmanship = \n| membership = \n| attendance = \n| former name = \n| bull date = \n| founded date = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} - but see note below -->\n| founder = [[Society of Jesus]]\n| dedication = [[Mary, mother of Jesus]]\n| dedicated date = \n| consecrated date = 15 August 1693<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.swlipka.pl/dla-pielgrzyma/historia|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka - Sanktuarium Maryjne o. Jezuici - Historia|website=www.swlipka.pl}}</ref>\n| cult = \n| relics = \n| events = \n| past bishop = \n| people = \n| status = \n| functional status = Active\n| heritage designation = \n| designated date = \n| architect =  \n| architectural type = \n| style = [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]]\n| years built = 1688-1693<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=VKsxAQAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+jezuici+1688&dq=swieta+lipka+jezuici+1688&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdgrjvgcroAhWhzzgGHVfaCiQQ6AEIgAEwCQ|title=Popularna encyklopedia powszechna|first=Wojciech|last=Adamski|date=January 2, 2001|publisher=Fogra|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n| groundbreaking = \n| completed date = \n| construction cost = \n| closed date = \n| demolished date = \n| capacity = \n| length = \n| width nave = \n| height = \n| diameter = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| other dimensions = \n| floor count = \n| floor area = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| dome quantity = \n| dome height outer = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| dome height inner = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| dome dia outer = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| dome dia inner = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| spire quantity = \n| spire height = \n| materials = \n| bells = \n| bells hung = \n| bell weight = \n| website = [http://www.swlipka.pl/ Link]\n| deanery = \n| archdeaconry = \n| episcopalarea = \n| archdiocese = [[Archdiocese of Warmia]]\n| metropolis = \n| diocese = \n}}\n\n'''\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Sanctuary''' ({{lang-pl|Sanktuarium w \u015awi\u0119tej Lipce}}; {{lang-de|Heiligelinde}}), in English known as the '''Holy Linden''', is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[basilica]] located in the small village of [[\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka]], in northeastern [[Poland]]. It serves as a [[pilgrimage]] site and a holy [[Shrines to the Virgin Mary|shrine]] dedicated to the [[Virgin Mary]]. Built during the late 17th century, the basilica is one of the best examples of [[Baroque architecture]] in Poland and in the world. It is also famous for its moving [[organ (music)|pipe organ]], possibly the finest church instrument ever constructed.\n\n== Cult ==\n[[File:\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 Pielgrzymkowy Kru\u017cganek i Kaplica Naro\u017cna 023.jpg|thumb|left|Cloisters]]\nThe semi-legendary cult was cultivated by locals since the 1300s, when a petty criminal carved a figurine of Mary in the nearby [[K\u0119trzyn]] prison following a [[Marian apparition]].<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=c-sjAQAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+objawila&dq=swieta+lipka+objawila&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiArZv6_8noAhUIxTgGHT5vDx0Q6AEITTAE|title=S\u0142ownik Warmii: historyczno-geograficzny|first=Jan|last=Ch\u0142osta|date=April 2, 2002|publisher=Littera|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mazury24.eu/atrakcje-turystyczne/sanktuarium-maryjne-swieta-lipka,360|title=Atrakcja turystyczna - Sanktuarium Maryjne \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|website=mazury24.eu}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.se.pl/styl-zycia/porady/sanktuarium-maryjne-w-swietej-lipce-aa-QMMu-xeSF-aZkz.html|title=Sanktuarium Maryjne, \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka - przewodnik, co warto zobaczy\u0107|website=www.se.pl}}</ref> He was then unexpectedly released and en route to [[Reszel]] he placed the figurine on a [[linden tree]] as a sign of gratitude.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto5\"/> The object was said to work wonders and had healing properties. [[Albert, Duke of Prussia]], visited the sacred place while pilgrimaging barefoot from [[K\u00f6nigsberg]] in 1519.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xWlZAAAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+1519&dq=swieta+lipka+1519&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUoZilgMroAhU0xzgGHdgPC0cQ6AEIKzAA|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|first=J\u00f3zef|last=Poklewski|date=April 2, 1974|publisher=Polskiej Akademii Nauk|via=Google Books}}</ref> This tradition was also previously observed by the [[Teutonic Knights]]. \n\nThe medieval shrine was destroyed during the [[Protestant Reformation]] in around 1524 and [[gallows]] were placed in the same spot to scare off the Catholic worshipers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=POdBAAAAYAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+szubienica&dq=swieta+lipka+szubienica&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiuvtCEgcroAhW5wjgGHVBRDCYQ6AEIKDAA|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|first=Jan|last=Ba\u0142dowski|date=April 2, 1985|publisher=Wydawn. PTTK \"Kraj\"|via=Google Books}}</ref> Almost a century later it was rebuilt by the personal secretary of king [[Sigismund III]], who purchased the land where the missing figurine once stood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=istMAQAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+sklepienie+zygmunt+iii&dq=swieta+lipka+sklepienie+zygmunt+iii&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHl5rZgsroAhVdwTgGHYGmCEAQ6AEIczAI|title=Kr\u00f3lowa korony polskiej: szkice z historji malarstwa i kultu Bogarodzicy w Polsce|first=Mieczys\u0142aw|last=Skrudlik|date=April 2, 1930|publisher=Bibljoteka religijna|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> A painting of Mary with Baby Jesus by a [[Belgium|Belgian]] master painter Bartholomew Pens from [[Elbing]] replaced the lost relic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=JhzWmLORVmUC&pg=PA203&dq=swieta+lipka+pens&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjq-beQgcroAhW0yzgGHaVRC6cQ6AEIOzAC#v=onepage&q=swieta+lipka+pens&f=false|title=Masuren: mit K\u00f6nigsberg, Danzig und Thorn|first=Maren|last=Rathke|date=April 2, 2010|publisher=Trescher Verlag|via=Google Books}}</ref> During the [[Swedish Deluge]], many of the priceless items from the chapel's treasury were hidden in [[Gda\u0144sk]] (Danzig) and survived the turmoil. As Catholicism remained the dominant religion in the region of [[Warmia]] (Ermland), devotees from across the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]] regularly journeyed to the place, particularly from [[Warsaw]] and [[Vilnius]].\n\nTo this day, the pilgrimage route from the town of Reszel to \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka is aligned with small Baroque shrines and linden trees, dating back to the 18th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encyklopedia.warmia.mazury.pl/index.php/Kapliczki_r%C3%B3%C5%BCa%C5%84cowe_przy_drodze_z_Reszla_do_%C5%9Awi%C4%99tej_Lipki|title=Kapliczki r\u00f3\u017ca\u0144cowe przy drodze z Reszla do \u015awi\u0119tej Lipki|website=Encyklopedia Warmii i Mazur}}</ref>\n\n== Basilica ==  \n[[File:Ruchome organy w \u015awi\u0119tej Lipce.jpg|thumb|left|The moving pipe organ]]\nThe church and [[convent]] were founded by the [[Society of Jesus]] and construction was initiated by Polish Cardinal [[Micha\u0142 Stefan Radziejowski]] in 1688.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The temple's consecration occurred on 15 August 1693. Due to the large number of arriving pilgrims, the facility was significantly enlarged over the years and a fortified [[cloister]] with domed tower-like chapels was completed in 1708,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xWlZAAAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+1708&dq=swieta+lipka+1708&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjR57qngsroAhWHyzgGHUtwAd4Q6AEIKzAA|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|first=J\u00f3zef|last=Poklewski|date=April 2, 1974|publisher=Polskiej Akademii Nauk|via=Google Books}}</ref> giving the overall structure a defensive appearance. The elaborate interior took over 50 years to be entirely finished and furnished. The church was further embellished with decoration through donations made by wealthy notables or pious monarchs such as [[Ladislaus IV of Poland|Ladislaus IV]], Queen [[Marie Casimire]] or [[Stanislaus I Leszczy\u0144ski]] and his wife [[Catherine Opali\u0144ska|Catherine]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=POdBAAAAYAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+leszczy%C5%84ski+sobieski&dq=swieta+lipka+leszczy%C5%84ski+sobieski&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc94ezgsroAhXRzzgGHUbXAg4Q6AEIKzAA|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|first=Jan|last=Ba\u0142dowski|date=April 2, 1985|publisher=Wydawn. PTTK \"Kraj\"|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe monumental [[altar]] was made between 1712 and 1714 by the finest sculptors present in Poland at the time. The object, composed of three main parts or [[Storey|storeys]], is adorned by the gilded figures of saints and [[martyrs]]. [[John III Sobieski]] gifted a painting to the Jesuits after his victory at the [[Battle of Vienna]] and it was later incorporated into the altarpiece.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> \n\n[[File:\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 Pielgrzymkowy Wn\u0119trze 018.jpg|thumb|right|The interior with main altar and vault frescoes]]\n\nThe ornate paintwork and [[fresco]]es on the [[Vault (architecture)|vault]] ceiling was completed in 1727.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7REaAAAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+sklepienie+zygmunt+iii+1727&dq=swieta+lipka+sklepienie+zygmunt+iii+1727&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja7cj2gsroAhWy4jgGHX25BigQ6AEIMDAB|title=S\u0142ownik biograficzny Warmii, Prus Ksi\u0105\u017c\u0119cych i Ziemi Malborskiej od po\u0142owy XV do ko\u0144ca XVIII wieku|first=Tadeusz|last=Oracki|date=April 2, 1988|publisher=Wydawn. \"Pojezierze\"|via=Google Books}}</ref>  They feature images of [[Saint Casimir]], Sigismund III and [[Hedwig of Silesia]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/> \n\nThe most distinctive attribute and a treasure of the sanctuary is the moving [[organ (music)|pipe organ]], erected in the years 1719-1721 by [[Johann Josua Mosengel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=32VKAAAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+organy&dq=swieta+lipka+organy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-yu---8noAhXTzjgGHQ5FCNMQ6AEIUTAF|title=The Polish Organ: Organ-cases in Poland as works of art|first1=Jerzy|last1=Go\u0142os|first2=Ewa|last2=Smulikowska|date=April 2, 1993|publisher=Sutkowski|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">{{Cite web|url=https://dziedzictwo.ekai.pl/@@sw_lipka_barokowe_organy|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka: barokowe organy|website=dziedzictwo.ekai.pl}}</ref> The decorative figures and sculptures move as the organ is being played, making it one of the most unique instruments ever made.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://proszewycieczki.wordpress.com/2018/11/20/swieta-lipka-barokowe-organy/|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka \u2013 barokowe organy|date=November 20, 2018}}</ref> In 1944, it was damaged but repaired soonafter.   \n\nThe [[Jesuits]] were eventually removed from the \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka monastery by the [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussians]] after the [[Partitions of Poland]] in the 18th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=vUYO5nTFJQUC&q=swieta+lipka+jezuici+1688&dq=swieta+lipka+jezuici+1688&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdgrjvgcroAhWhzzgGHVfaCiQQ6AEITzAE|title=Polski slownik biograficzny: Dunin-Girdwoy\u0144|date=April 2, 1935|publisher=Sk\u0142ad g\u0142\u00f3wny w ksi\u0119g, Gebethnera i Wolffa|via=Google Books}}</ref> They returned to the convent in 1932. After [[World War II]], when Warmia [[Recovered Territories|returned]] to Poland under the [[Potsdam Agreement]], \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka was transformed into an important sanctuary, alongside the [[Jasna G\u00f3ra Monastery]]. Furthermore, it remains an outstanding example of Baroque art and architecture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hhw7AQAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+baroku+w+polsce&dq=swieta+lipka+baroku+w+polsce&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjPudiIg8roAhWMxTgGHWZ4AS4Q6AEIYjAG|title=S\u0142ownik geografii turystycznej Polski|first1=Poland Komitet do Spraw|last1=Turystyki|first2=Jerzy|last2=Brinken|date=April 2, 1956|publisher=Komitet dla Spraw Turystyki|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons|Category:Sanctuary of Saint Mary in \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Marian shrines]]\n[[Category:Basilica churches in Poland]]\n[[Category:Baroque architecture in Poland]]\n[[Category:Christian monasteries in Poland]]\n[[Category:Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth]]\n[[Category:Churches in Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox church\n| denomination = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| name = \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Sanctuary\n| other name =  Holy Linden Basilica\n| image = File:\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 Pielgrzymkowy 072.jpg\n| imagesize = 240\n| imagealt = \n| caption = The basilica in 2012\n| pushpin map = \n| pushpin label position = \n| pushpin map alt = \n| relief = \n| pushpin mapsize = \n| map caption = \n| coordinates =\n| country = [[Poland]]\n| osgridref = <!-- {{gbmappingsmall| TEXT}} -->\n| osgraw = <!--  TEXT -->\n| location = [[\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka]], [[Warmia]]\n| previous denomination = \n| churchmanship = \n| membership = \n| attendance = \n| former name = \n| bull date = \n| founded date = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} - but see note below -->\n| founder = [[Society of Jesus]]\n| dedication = [[Mary, mother of Jesus]]\n| dedicated date = \n| consecrated date = 15 August 1693<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.swlipka.pl/dla-pielgrzyma/historia|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka - Sanktuarium Maryjne o. Jezuici - Historia|website=www.swlipka.pl}}</ref>\n| cult = \n| relics = \n| events = \n| past bishop = \n| people = \n| status = \n| functional status = Active\n| heritage designation = \n| designated date = \n| architect =  \n| architectural type = \n| style = [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]]\n| years built = 1688-1693<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=VKsxAQAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+jezuici+1688&dq=swieta+lipka+jezuici+1688&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdgrjvgcroAhWhzzgGHVfaCiQQ6AEIgAEwCQ|title=Popularna encyklopedia powszechna|first=Wojciech|last=Adamski|date=January 2, 2001|publisher=Fogra|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n| groundbreaking = \n| completed date = \n| construction cost = \n| closed date = \n| demolished date = \n| capacity = \n| length = \n| width nave = \n| height = \n| diameter = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| other dimensions = \n| floor count = \n| floor area = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| dome quantity = \n| dome height outer = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| dome height inner = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| dome dia outer = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| dome dia inner = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| spire quantity = \n| spire height = \n| materials = \n| bells = \n| bells hung = \n| bell weight = \n| website = [http://www.swlipka.pl/ Link]\n| deanery = \n| archdeaconry = \n| episcopalarea = \n| archdiocese = [[Archdiocese of Warmia]]\n| metropolis = \n| diocese = \n}}\n\n'''\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Sanctuary''' ({{lang-pl|Sanktuarium w \u015awi\u0119tej Lipce}}; {{lang-de|Heiligelinde}}), in English known as the '''Holy Linden''', is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[basilica]] located in the small village of [[\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka]], in northeastern [[Poland]]. It serves as a [[pilgrimage]] site and a holy [[Shrines to the Virgin Mary|shrine]] dedicated to the [[Virgin Mary]]. Built during the late 17th century, the basilica is one of the best examples of [[Baroque architecture]] in Poland and in the world. It is also famous for its moving [[organ (music)|pipe organ]], possibly the finest church instrument ever constructed.\n\n== Cult ==\n[[File:\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 Pielgrzymkowy Kru\u017cganek i Kaplica Naro\u017cna 023.jpg|thumb|left|Cloisters]]\nThe semi-legendary cult was cultivated by locals since the 1300s, when a petty criminal carved a figurine of Mary in the nearby [[K\u0119trzyn]] prison following a [[Marian apparition]].<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=c-sjAQAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+objawila&dq=swieta+lipka+objawila&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiArZv6_8noAhUIxTgGHT5vDx0Q6AEITTAE|title=S\u0142ownik Warmii: historyczno-geograficzny|first=Jan|last=Ch\u0142osta|date=April 2, 2002|publisher=Littera|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mazury24.eu/atrakcje-turystyczne/sanktuarium-maryjne-swieta-lipka,360|title=Atrakcja turystyczna - Sanktuarium Maryjne \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|website=mazury24.eu}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.se.pl/styl-zycia/porady/sanktuarium-maryjne-w-swietej-lipce-aa-QMMu-xeSF-aZkz.html|title=Sanktuarium Maryjne, \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka - przewodnik, co warto zobaczy\u0107|website=www.se.pl}}</ref> He was then unexpectedly released and en route to [[Reszel]] he placed the figurine on a [[linden tree]] as a sign of gratitude.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto5\"/> The object was said to work wonders and had healing properties. [[Albert, Duke of Prussia]], visited the sacred place while pilgrimaging barefoot from [[K\u00f6nigsberg]] in 1519.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xWlZAAAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+1519&dq=swieta+lipka+1519&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUoZilgMroAhU0xzgGHdgPC0cQ6AEIKzAA|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|first=J\u00f3zef|last=Poklewski|date=April 2, 1974|publisher=Polskiej Akademii Nauk|via=Google Books}}</ref> This tradition was also previously observed by the [[Teutonic Knights]]. \n\nThe medieval shrine was destroyed during the [[Protestant Reformation]] in around 1524 and [[gallows]] were placed in the same spot to scare off the Catholic worshipers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=POdBAAAAYAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+szubienica&dq=swieta+lipka+szubienica&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiuvtCEgcroAhW5wjgGHVBRDCYQ6AEIKDAA|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|first=Jan|last=Ba\u0142dowski|date=April 2, 1985|publisher=Wydawn. PTTK \"Kraj\"|via=Google Books}}</ref> Almost a century later it was rebuilt by the personal secretary of king [[Sigismund III]], who purchased the land where the missing figurine once stood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=istMAQAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+sklepienie+zygmunt+iii&dq=swieta+lipka+sklepienie+zygmunt+iii&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHl5rZgsroAhVdwTgGHYGmCEAQ6AEIczAI|title=Kr\u00f3lowa korony polskiej: szkice z historji malarstwa i kultu Bogarodzicy w Polsce|first=Mieczys\u0142aw|last=Skrudlik|date=April 2, 1930|publisher=Bibljoteka religijna|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> A painting of Mary with Baby Jesus by a [[Belgium|Belgian]] master painter Bartholomew Pens from [[Elbing]] replaced the lost relic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=JhzWmLORVmUC&pg=PA203&dq=swieta+lipka+pens&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjq-beQgcroAhW0yzgGHaVRC6cQ6AEIOzAC#v=onepage&q=swieta+lipka+pens&f=false|title=Masuren: mit K\u00f6nigsberg, Danzig und Thorn|first=Maren|last=Rathke|date=April 2, 2010|publisher=Trescher Verlag|via=Google Books}}</ref> During the [[Swedish Deluge]], many of the priceless items from the chapel's treasury were hidden in [[Gda\u0144sk]] (Danzig) and survived the turmoil. As Catholicism remained the dominant religion in the region of [[Warmia]] (Ermland), devotees from across the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]] regularly journeyed to the place, particularly from [[Warsaw]] and [[Vilnius]].\n\nTo this day, the pilgrimage route from the town of Reszel to \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka is aligned with small Baroque shrines and linden trees, dating back to the 18th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encyklopedia.warmia.mazury.pl/index.php/Kapliczki_r%C3%B3%C5%BCa%C5%84cowe_przy_drodze_z_Reszla_do_%C5%9Awi%C4%99tej_Lipki|title=Kapliczki r\u00f3\u017ca\u0144cowe przy drodze z Reszla do \u015awi\u0119tej Lipki|website=Encyklopedia Warmii i Mazur}}</ref>\n\n== Basilica ==  \n[[File:Ruchome organy w \u015awi\u0119tej Lipce.jpg|thumb|left|The moving pipe organ]]\nThe church and [[convent]] were founded by the [[Society of Jesus]] and construction was initiated by Polish Cardinal [[Micha\u0142 Stefan Radziejowski]] in 1688.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The temple's consecration occurred on 15 August 1693. Due to the large number of arriving pilgrims, the facility was significantly enlarged over the years and a fortified [[cloister]] with domed tower-like chapels was completed in 1708,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xWlZAAAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+1708&dq=swieta+lipka+1708&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjR57qngsroAhWHyzgGHUtwAd4Q6AEIKzAA|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|first=J\u00f3zef|last=Poklewski|date=April 2, 1974|publisher=Polskiej Akademii Nauk|via=Google Books}}</ref> giving the overall structure a defensive appearance. The elaborate interior took over 50 years to be entirely finished and furnished. The church was further embellished with decoration through donations made by wealthy notables or pious monarchs such as [[Ladislaus IV]], Queen [[Marie Casimire]] or [[Stanislaus I Leszczy\u0144ski]] and his wife [[Catherine Opali\u0144ska|Catherine]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=POdBAAAAYAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+leszczy%C5%84ski+sobieski&dq=swieta+lipka+leszczy%C5%84ski+sobieski&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc94ezgsroAhXRzzgGHUbXAg4Q6AEIKzAA|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka|first=Jan|last=Ba\u0142dowski|date=April 2, 1985|publisher=Wydawn. PTTK \"Kraj\"|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe monumental [[altar]] was made between 1712 and 1714 by the finest sculptors present in Poland at the time. The object, composed of three main parts or [[Storey|storeys]], is adorned by the gilded figures of saints and [[martyrs]]. [[John III Sobieski]] gifted a painting to the Jesuits after his victory at the [[Battle of Vienna]] and it was later incorporated into the altarpiece.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> \n\n[[File:\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 Pielgrzymkowy Wn\u0119trze 018.jpg|thumb|right|The interior with main altar and vault frescoes]]\n\nThe ornate paintwork and [[fresco]]es on the [[Vault (architecture)|vault]] ceiling was completed in 1727.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7REaAAAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+sklepienie+zygmunt+iii+1727&dq=swieta+lipka+sklepienie+zygmunt+iii+1727&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja7cj2gsroAhWy4jgGHX25BigQ6AEIMDAB|title=S\u0142ownik biograficzny Warmii, Prus Ksi\u0105\u017c\u0119cych i Ziemi Malborskiej od po\u0142owy XV do ko\u0144ca XVIII wieku|first=Tadeusz|last=Oracki|date=April 2, 1988|publisher=Wydawn. \"Pojezierze\"|via=Google Books}}</ref>  They feature images of [[Saint Casimir]], Sigismund III and [[Hedwig of Silesia]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/> \n\nThe most distinctive attribute and a treasure of the sanctuary is the moving [[organ (music)|pipe organ]], erected in the years 1719-1721 by [[Johann Josua Mosengel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=32VKAAAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+organy&dq=swieta+lipka+organy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-yu---8noAhXTzjgGHQ5FCNMQ6AEIUTAF|title=The Polish Organ: Organ-cases in Poland as works of art|first1=Jerzy|last1=Go\u0142os|first2=Ewa|last2=Smulikowska|date=April 2, 1993|publisher=Sutkowski|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">{{Cite web|url=https://dziedzictwo.ekai.pl/@@sw_lipka_barokowe_organy|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka: barokowe organy|website=dziedzictwo.ekai.pl}}</ref> The decorative figures and sculptures move as the organ is being played, making it one of the most unique instruments ever made.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://proszewycieczki.wordpress.com/2018/11/20/swieta-lipka-barokowe-organy/|title=\u015awi\u0119ta Lipka \u2013 barokowe organy|date=November 20, 2018}}</ref> In 1944, it was damaged but repaired soonafter.   \n\nThe [[Jesuits]] were eventually removed from the \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka monastery by the [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussians]] after the [[Partitions of Poland]] in the 18th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=vUYO5nTFJQUC&q=swieta+lipka+jezuici+1688&dq=swieta+lipka+jezuici+1688&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdgrjvgcroAhWhzzgGHVfaCiQQ6AEITzAE|title=Polski slownik biograficzny: Dunin-Girdwoy\u0144|date=April 2, 1935|publisher=Sk\u0142ad g\u0142\u00f3wny w ksi\u0119g, Gebethnera i Wolffa|via=Google Books}}</ref> They returned to the convent in 1932. After [[World War II]], when Warmia [[Recovered Territories|returned]] to Poland under the [[Potsdam Agreement]], \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka was transformed into an important sanctuary, alongside the [[Jasna G\u00f3ra Monastery]]. Furthermore, it remains an outstanding example of Baroque art and architecture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hhw7AQAAIAAJ&q=swieta+lipka+baroku+w+polsce&dq=swieta+lipka+baroku+w+polsce&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjPudiIg8roAhWMxTgGHWZ4AS4Q6AEIYjAG|title=S\u0142ownik geografii turystycznej Polski|first1=Poland Komitet do Spraw|last1=Turystyki|first2=Jerzy|last2=Brinken|date=April 2, 1956|publisher=Komitet dla Spraw Turystyki|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons|Category:Sanctuary of Saint Mary in \u015awi\u0119ta Lipka}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Marian shrines]]\n[[Category:Basilica churches in Poland]]\n[[Category:Baroque architecture in Poland]]\n[[Category:Christian monasteries in Poland]]\n[[Category:Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth]]\n[[Category:Churches in Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Ladislaus IV\u2192Ladislaus IV of Poland", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%9Awi%C4%99ta_Lipka_Sanctuary"}
